    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Missile Shield, Under Fire</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Clayton R Swope letter warns that national missile defense system would likely damage US relations with Europe (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As you report in your May 2 news article, the creation of a national missile defense system would likely damage the United States' relations with European countries because of its inability to protect Europe from missile strikes. Recent debate over a missile defense system has shown that it has many disadvantages.</p>
        <p>It seems that the $60 billion system will only isolate America from its most vital allies in Europe -- the allies the United States needs if it ever hopes to achieve global security.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As you report in your May 2 news article, the creation of a national missile defense system would likely damage the United States' relations with European countries because of its inability to protect Europe from missile strikes. Recent debate over a missile defense system has shown that it has many disadvantages.</p>
        <p>It seems that the $60 billion system will only isolate America from its most vital allies in Europe -- the allies the United States needs if it ever hopes to achieve global security.</p>
        <p>And not only would it alienate Russia by violating the Antiballistic Missile Treaty, but it would also drive China to militarize further.</p>
        <p>Is it worth sacrificing both American and world security in the name of a national missile defense system?</p>
        <p>CLAYTON R. SWOPE  Notre Dame, Ind., May 2, 2000</p>
      </block>
